---

## What is Zolto?

Zolto is a **unified document language** that combines the simplicity of
Markdown with the power of structured layout, mathematics, diagrams, and
interactive components — all in one coherent syntax.

You already know 80% of it. If you can write Markdown, you can write Zolto.

<cards cols="3">
  <card title="Markdown Native" thumbnail="">
  Headings, bold, italic, tables, code, links — all standard CommonMark.
  No surprises.
  </card>
  <card title="Tag Everything Else">
  Math, diagrams, callouts, cards, charts — one consistent `<Tag>` syntax.
  </card>
  <card title="Components">
  Define reusable layout fragments with props and slots. Ship your own
  design system in `.zl`.
  </card>
</cards>

---

## The Two Rules

<tip title="Rule 1">
Write **prose, headings, lists, and tables** using standard Markdown.
</tip>

<tip title="Rule 2">
Use `<Tag attr="value">…</Tag>` for **everything beyond Markdown** — math,
callouts, diagrams, charts, layouts.
</tip>

That's it. There is no `@directive` syntax. There are no `$dollar$` math
delimiters. One tag format, everywhere.

---

## A Quick Tour

### Math

Inline: the area of a circle is <m>A = \pi r^2</m>.

Block:

<math>
\sum_{k=1}^{n} k = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}
</math>

### Callouts

<note>
This is a note. Use it for neutral, supplementary information.
</note>

<warning>
This is a warning. Use it when the reader should be careful.
</warning>

<tip>
This is a tip. Use it for helpful hints and best practices.
</tip>

### Code

```javascript title="greet.js"
const greet = (name) => `Hello, ${name}! Welcome to Zolto.`;
console.log(greet('World'));
```

