## Interactive Components

### Tabs

<tabs>
  <tab title="HTML Output">
  Zolto renders to clean, semantic HTML5. You can export the result as a
  self-contained HTML file with all CSS inlined.
  </tab>
  <tab title="PDF Export">
  Use File → Export → PDF to print-ready output. KaTeX math, diagrams, and
  charts are all vector-rendered.
  </tab>
  <tab title="Markdown Export">
  Export back to CommonMark + GFM. Tag blocks are rendered to their closest
  Markdown equivalent where possible.
  </tab>
</tabs>

### Accordion

<accordion>
  <item title="Is Zolto backwards-compatible with Markdown?">
  Yes. All valid CommonMark is valid Zolto. You can open any `.md` file in
  Zolto and it will render correctly. Zolto extends Markdown; it does not
  replace it.
  </item>
  <item title="Can I use LaTeX math?">
  You use KaTeX syntax — which is a strict superset of the math subset of
  LaTeX. Most LaTeX math expressions work as-is inside `<math>` and `<m>` tags.
  </item>
  <item title="What about dollar-sign math?">
  Dollar signs are not math delimiters in Zolto. Write `<m>E = mc^2</m>`,
  not `$E = mc^2$`. Dollar signs render as literal `$` characters — useful
  for prices, currencies, and shell prompts.
  </item>
</accordion>

